Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: New Mauritius Hotels; Naiade Resorts

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-08-19T15:38:16Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-19/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-new-mauritius-hotels-naiade-resorts.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index advanced 0.7 percent to 1,185.51 by the 3 p.m. close in
Accra, the highest since July 25.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for a third day, sliding 1.3
percent to 1,920.16 by the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
Kenya’s All-Share Index advanced for a second day, climbing 0.4
percent to 62.93 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index snapped a three-day rally,
weakening 0.5 percent to 22,724.02 by the 2:30 p.m. close in
Lagos, according to a statement on the bourse’s website.
Namibia’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098)  gained less than 0.1
percent to 754.90 by the 4 p.m. end of trading in the capital
Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  New Mauritius Hotels Ltd. (NMH)  , the nation’s largest
leisure operator by market value, fell 2 rupees, or 2.4 percent,
to 83 rupees, the lowest since March 2009. A slowdown in the
global economy may impact Mauritius’s tourism, textiles and
financial  service industries , according to Imrith Ramtohul, a
senior investment manager who helps oversee 6 billion rupees
($212.8 million) at Mauritius Union Group.  Naiade Resorts Ltd. (NRL)  , Mauritius’s third-biggest
tourism company, declined 0.6 rupee, or 2.1 percent, to 28.50
rupees.  State Bank of Mauritius Ltd. (SBM)  , the country’s
second-largest lender by market value, slumped 2.5 rupees, or
2.8 percent, to 87.5 rupees.  To contact the reporter on this story:
